InterfaceSVGAnimatedString.summary: The SVGAnimatedString interface represents string attributes which can be animated from each SVG declaration. You need to create SVG attribute before doing anything else, everything should be declared inside this.
InterfaceSVGAnimatedString.title: SVGAnimatedString

animate.html#AnimateElement.summary: This element implements the SVGAnimateElement interface.
animate.html#AnimateElement.title: <animate>

animate.html#AnimateMotionElement.summary: The animateMotion element causes a referenced element to move along a motion path.
animate.html#AnimateMotionElement.title: <animateMotion>

animate.html#AnimateTransformElement.summary: The animateTransform element animates a transformation attribute on a target element, thereby allowing animations to control translation, scaling, rotation and/or skewing.
animate.html#AnimateTransformElement.title: <animateTransform>

animate.html#FillAttribute.summary: The fill attribute has two different meaning: For shapes and text it's a presentation attribute that lets define the color (or any SVG paint servers like gradients or patterns) used to paint the element; for animation it lets define what is the final state of the animation.
animate.html#FillAttribute.title: fill

animate.html#InterfaceSVGAnimateTransfor.title: SVGAnimateTransformElement

animate.html#InterfaceSVGAnimationElemen.summary: The SVGAnimationElement interface is the base interface for all of the animation element interfaces: SVGAnimateElement, SVGSetElement, SVGAnimateColorElement, SVGAnimateMotionElement and SVGAnimateTransformElement.
animate.html#InterfaceSVGAnimationElemen.title: SVGAnimationElement

animate.html#SetElement.summary: The set element provides a simple means of just setting the value of an attribute for a specified duration. It supports all attribute types, including those that cannot reasonably be interpolated, such as string and boolean values. The set element is non-additive. The additive and accumulate attributes are not allowed, and will be ignored if specified.
animate.html#SetElement.title: <set>

animate.html#__svg__SVGAnimationElement_.summary: The SVGAnimationElement.targetElement property refers to the element which is being animated. If no target element is being animated (for example, because the href attribute specifies an unknown element), the value returned is null.
animate.html#__svg__SVGAnimationElement_.title: targetElement

coords.html#TransformAttribute.summary: The transform attribute defines a list of transform definitions that are applied to an element and the element's children.
coords.html#TransformAttribute.title: transform

filters.html#InterfaceSVGFilterElement.summary: The SVGFilterElement interface provides access to the properties of filter elements, as well as methods to manipulate them.
filters.html#InterfaceSVGFilterElement.title: SVGFilterElement

filters.html#InterfaceSVGFilterPrimitive.summary: The SVGFilterPrimitiveStandardAttributes interface defines the set of DOM attributes that are common across the filter primitive interfaces.
filters.html#InterfaceSVGFilterPrimitive.title: SVGFilterPrimitiveStandardAttributes

filters.html#feBlendElement.summary: The feBlend SVG filter primitive composes two objects together ruled by a certain blending mode. This is similar to what is known from image editing software when blending two layers. The mode is defined by the mode attribute.
filters.html#feBlendElement.title: <feBlend>

filters.html#feColorMatrixElement.summary: The feColorMatrix SVG filter element changes colors based on a transformation matrix. Every pixel's color value (represented by an [R,G,B,A] vector) is matrix multiplied to create a new color:
filters.html#feColorMatrixElement.title: <feColorMatrix>

filters.html#feComponentTransferElement.summary: Th feComponentTransfer SVG filter primitive performs color-component-wise remapping of data for each pixel. It allows operations like brightness adjustment, contrast adjustment, color balance or thresholding.
filters.html#feComponentTransferElement.title: <feComponentTransfer>

filters.html#feCompositeElement.summary: The feComposite SVG filter primitive performs the combination of two input images pixel-wise in image space using one of the Porter-Duff compositing operations: over, in, atop, out, xor, and lighter. Additionally, a component-wise arithmetic operation (with the result clamped between [0..1]) can be applied.
filters.html#feCompositeElement.title: <feComposite>

filters.html#feConvolveMatrixElement.summary: The feConvolveMatrix SVG filter primitive applies a matrix convolution filter effect. A convolution combines pixels in the input image with neighboring pixels to produce a resulting image. A wide variety of imaging operations can be achieved through convolutions, including blurring, edge detection, sharpening, embossing and beveling.
filters.html#feConvolveMatrixElement.title: <feConvolveMatrix>

filters.html#feDiffuseLightingElement.summary: The feDiffuseLighting SVG filter primitive lights an image using the alpha channel as a bump map. The resulting image, which is an RGBA opaque image, depends on the light color, light position and surface geometry of the input bump map.
filters.html#feDiffuseLightingElement.title: <feDiffuseLighting>

filters.html#feDisplacementMapElement.summary: The feDisplacementMap SVG filter primitive uses the pixel values from the image from in2 to spatially displace the image from in.
filters.html#feDisplacementMapElement.title: <feDisplacementMap>

filters.html#feDistantLightElement.summary: The feDistantLight filter primitive defines a distant light source that can be used within a lighting filter primitive: feDiffuseLighting or feSpecularLighting.
filters.html#feDistantLightElement.title: <feDistantLight>

filters.html#feFloodElement.summary: The feFlood SVG filter primitive fills the filter subregion with the color and opacity defined by flood-color and flood-opacity.
filters.html#feFloodElement.title: <feFlood>

filters.html#feFuncAElement.summary: The feFuncA SVG filter primitive defines the transfer function for the alpha component of the input graphic of its parent feComponentTransfer element.
filters.html#feFuncAElement.title: <feFuncA>

filters.html#feFuncBElement.summary: The feFuncB SVG filter primitive defines the transfer function for the blue component of the input graphic of its parent feComponentTransfer element.
filters.html#feFuncBElement.title: <feFuncB>

filters.html#feFuncGElement.summary: The feFuncG SVG filter primitive defines the transfer function for the green component of the input graphic of its parent feComponentTransfer element.
filters.html#feFuncGElement.title: <feFuncG>

filters.html#feFuncRElement.summary: The feFuncR SVG filter primitive defines the transfer function for the red component of the input graphic of its parent feComponentTransfer element.
filters.html#feFuncRElement.title: <feFuncR>

filters.html#feGaussianBlurElement.summary: The feGaussianBlur SVG filter primitive blurs the input image by the amount specified in stdDeviation, which defines the bell-curve.
filters.html#feGaussianBlurElement.title: <feGaussianBlur>

filters.html#feImageElement.summary: The feImage SVG filter primitive fetches image data from an external source and provides the pixel data as output (meaning if the external source is an SVG image, it is rasterized.)
filters.html#feImageElement.title: <feImage>

filters.html#feMergeElement.summary: The feMerge SVG element allows filter effects to be applied concurrently instead of sequentially. This is achieved by other filters storing their output via the result attribute and then accessing it in a feMergeNode child.
filters.html#feMergeElement.title: <feMerge>

filters.html#feMergeNodeElement.summary: The feMergeNode takes the result of another filter to be processed by its parent feMerge.
filters.html#feMergeNodeElement.title: <feMergeNode>

filters.html#feMorphologyElement.summary: The feMorphology SVG filter primitive is used to erode or dilate the input image. It's usefulness lies especially in fattening or thinning effects.
filters.html#feMorphologyElement.title: <feMorphology>

filters.html#feOffsetDxAttribute.summary: The dx attribute indicates a shift along the x-axis on the position of an element or its content.
filters.html#feOffsetDxAttribute.title: dx

filters.html#feOffsetDyAttribute.summary: The dy attribute indicates a shift along the y-axis on the position of an element or its content.
filters.html#feOffsetDyAttribute.title: dy

filters.html#feOffsetElement.summary: The feOffset SVG filter primitive allows to offset the input image. The input image as a whole is offset by the values specified in the dx and dy attributes.
filters.html#feOffsetElement.title: <feOffset>

filters.html#fePointLightElement.summary: The fePointLight filter primitive defines a light source which allows to create a point light effect. It that can be used within a lighting filter primitive: feDiffuseLighting or feSpecularLighting.
filters.html#fePointLightElement.title: <fePointLight>

filters.html#fePointLightXAttribute.summary: The x attribute defines a x-axis coordinate in the user coordinate system.
filters.html#fePointLightXAttribute.title: x

filters.html#fePointLightYAttribute.summary: The y attribute defines a y-axis coordinate in the user coordinate system.
filters.html#fePointLightYAttribute.title: y

filters.html#feSpecularLightingElement.summary: The feSpecularLighting SVG filter primitive lights a source graphic using the alpha channel as a bump map. The resulting image is an RGBA image based on the light color. The lighting calculation follows the standard specular component of the Phong lighting model. The resulting image depends on the light color, light position and surface geometry of the input bump map. The result of the lighting calculation is added. The filter primitive assumes that the viewer is at infinity in the z direction.
filters.html#feSpecularLightingElement.title: <feSpecularLighting>

filters.html#feSpotLightElement.summary: The feSpotLight SVG filter primitive defines a light source which allows to create a spotlight effect. It that can be used within a lighting filter primitive: feDiffuseLighting or feSpecularLighting.
filters.html#feSpotLightElement.title: <feSpotLight>

filters.html#feSpotLightXAttribute.summary: The x attribute defines a x-axis coordinate in the user coordinate system.
filters.html#feSpotLightXAttribute.title: x

filters.html#feSpotLightYAttribute.summary: The y attribute defines a y-axis coordinate in the user coordinate system.
filters.html#feSpotLightYAttribute.title: y

filters.html#feTileElement.summary: The feTile SVG filter primitive allows to fill a target rectangle with a repeated, tiled pattern of an input image. The effect is similar to the one of a pattern.
filters.html#feTileElement.title: <feTile>

filters.html#feTurbulenceElement.summary: The feTurbulence SVG filter primitive creates an image using the Perlin turbulence function. It allows the synthesis of artificial textures like clouds or marble. The resulting image will fill the entire filter primitive subregion.

notes: Partially supported, see bug 12382004.
Partially supported, see bug 12382004.
Partially supported, see bug 12382004.

filters.html#feTurbulenceElement.title: <feTurbulence>

interact.html#CursorElementXAttribute.summary: The x attribute defines a x-axis coordinate in the user coordinate system.
interact.html#CursorElementXAttribute.title: x

interact.html#CursorElementYAttribute.summary: The y attribute defines a y-axis coordinate in the user coordinate system.
interact.html#CursorElementYAttribute.title: y

interact.html#PointerEventsProperty.summary: The  pointer-events CSS property sets under what circumstances (if any) a particular graphic element can become the target of mouse events.
interact.html#PointerEventsProperty.title: pointer-events

interact.html#PointerEventsProperty.summary: The pointer-events attribute is a presentation attribute that lets define whether or when an element may be the target of a mouse event.
interact.html#PointerEventsProperty.title: pointer-events

linking.html#InterfaceSVGAElement.summary: The SVGAElement interface provides access to the properties of a element, as well as methods to manipulate them.
linking.html#InterfaceSVGAElement.title: SVGAElement

linking.html#Links.summary: The a SVG element creates a hyperlink to other web pages, files, locations within the same page, email addresses, or any other URL.
linking.html#Links.title: <a>

linking.html#ViewElement.summary: A view is a defined way to view the image, like a zoom level or a detail view.
linking.html#ViewElement.title: <view>

masking.html#ClipPathProperty.summary: The clip-path CSS property creates a clipping region that sets what part of an element should be shown. Parts that are inside the region are shown, while those outside are hidden.
masking.html#ClipPathProperty.title: clip-path

masking.html#ClipPathProperty.summary: The clip-path presentation attribute defines or associates a clipping path with the element it is related to.
masking.html#ClipPathProperty.title: clip-path

masking.html#ClipProperty.summary: The clip attribute is a presentation attribute defining the visible region of an element.
masking.html#ClipProperty.title: clip

masking.html#EstablishingANewClippingPat.summary: The clipPath SVG element defines a clipping path. A clipping path is used/referenced using the clip-path property.
masking.html#EstablishingANewClippingPat.title: <clipPath>

masking.html#InterfaceSVGClipPathElement.summary: The SVGClipPathElement interface provides access to the properties of clipPath elements, as well as methods to manipulate them.
masking.html#InterfaceSVGClipPathElement.title: SVGClipPathElement

masking.html#InterfaceSVGMaskElement.summary: The SVGMaskElement interface provides access to the properties of mask elements, as well as methods to manipulate them.
masking.html#InterfaceSVGMaskElement.title: SVGMaskElement

masking.html#MaskElementXAttribute.summary: The x attribute defines a x-axis coordinate in the user coordinate system.
masking.html#MaskElementXAttribute.title: x

masking.html#MaskElementYAttribute.summary: The y attribute defines a y-axis coordinate in the user coordinate system.
masking.html#MaskElementYAttribute.title: y

masking.html#MaskProperty.summary: The mask CSS property hides an element (partially or fully) by masking or clipping the image at specific points.

chrome.notes: While the property is recognized, values applied to it don't have any effect.
The prefixed property can be used with SVG and HTML with a slightly different syntax, which allows setting the non-standard -webkit-mask-attachment property.

firefox.notes: From Firefox 10, the default color space when handling masks is sRGB. Previously, the default and only supported color space was linear RGB. This changes the appearance of mask effects, but brings Firefox into compliance with the second edition of the SVG 1.1 specification.

opera.notes: While the property is recognized, values applied to it don't have any effect.
The prefixed property can be used with SVG and HTML with a slightly different syntax, which allows setting the non-standard -webkit-mask-attachment property.

safari.notes: While the property is recognized, values applied to it don't have any effect.
The prefixed property can be used with SVG and HTML with a slightly different syntax, which allows setting the non-standard -webkit-mask-attachment property.

masking.html#MaskProperty.title: mask

masking.html#MaskProperty.summary: The mask attribute is a presentation attribute mainly used to bind a given mask element with the element the attribute belong to.
masking.html#MaskProperty.title: mask

masking.html#Masking.summary: The mask element defines an alpha mask for compositing the current object into the background. A mask is used/referenced using the mask property.
masking.html#Masking.title: <mask>

metadata.html#MetadataElement.summary: The metadata SVG element allows to add metadata to SVG content. Metadata is structured information about data. The contents of metadata elements should be elements from other XML namespaces such as RDF, FOAF, etc.
metadata.html#MetadataElement.title: <metadata>

painting.html#ColorInterpolationProperty.summary: The color-interpolation attribute specifies the color space for gradient interpolations, color animations, and alpha compositing.
painting.html#ColorInterpolationProperty.title: color-interpolation

painting.html#FillOpacityProperty.summary: The fill-opacity attribute is a presentation attribute defining the opacity of the paint server (color, gradient, pattern, etc) applied to a shape.
painting.html#FillOpacityProperty.title: fill-opacity

painting.html#FillProperty.summary: The fill attribute has two different meaning: For shapes and text it's a presentation attribute that lets define the color (or any SVG paint servers like gradients or patterns) used to paint the element; for animation it lets define what is the final state of the animation.
painting.html#FillProperty.title: fill

painting.html#FillRuleProperty.summary: The fill-rule attribute is a presentation attribute defining the algorithm to use to determine the inside part of a shape.
painting.html#FillRuleProperty.title: fill-rule

painting.html#MarkerElement.summary: The marker element defines the graphic that is to be used for drawing arrowheads or polymarkers on a given path, line, polyline or polygon element.
painting.html#MarkerElement.title: <marker>

painting.html#StrokeDasharrayProperty.summary: The stroke-dasharray attribute is a presentation attribute defining the pattern of dashes and gaps used to paint the outline of the shape;
painting.html#StrokeDasharrayProperty.title: stroke-dasharray

painting.html#StrokeDashoffsetProperty.summary: The stroke-dashoffset attribute is a presentation attribute defining an offset on the rendering of the associated dash array.
painting.html#StrokeDashoffsetProperty.title: stroke-dashoffset

painting.html#StrokeLinecapProperty.summary: The stroke-linecap attribute is a presentation attribute defining the shape to be used at the end of open subpaths when they are stroked.
painting.html#StrokeLinecapProperty.title: stroke-linecap

painting.html#StrokeLinejoinProperty.summary: The stroke-linejoin attribute is a presentation attribute defining the shape to be used at the corners of paths when they are stroked.
painting.html#StrokeLinejoinProperty.title: stroke-linejoin

painting.html#StrokeMiterlimitProperty.summary: The stroke-miterlimit attribute is a presentation attribute defining a limit on the ratio of the miter length to the stroke-width used to draw a miter join. When the limit is exceeded, the join is converted from a miter to a bevel.
painting.html#StrokeMiterlimitProperty.title: stroke-miterlimit

painting.html#StrokeOpacityProperty.summary: The stroke-opacity attribute is a presentation attribute defining the opacity of the paint server (color, gradient, pattern, etc) applied to the stroke of a shape.
painting.html#StrokeOpacityProperty.title: stroke-opacity

painting.html#StrokeProperty.summary: The stroke attribute is a presentation attribute defining the color (or any SVG paint servers like gradients or patterns) used to paint the outline of the shape;
painting.html#StrokeProperty.title: stroke

painting.html#StrokeWidthProperty.summary: The stroke-width attribute is a presentation attribute defining the width of the stroke to be applied to the shape.
painting.html#StrokeWidthProperty.title: stroke-width

painting.html#TextRenderingProperty.summary: The text-rendering CSS property provides information to the rendering engine about what to optimize for when rendering text.

notes: This property is only supported on Windows and Linux.
Initial versions had bugs on Windows and Linux that broke font substitition, small-caps, letter-spacing or caused text to overlap.
This property is only supported on Windows and Linux.
The optimizeSpeed option has no effect on Firefox 4 because the standard code for text rendering is already fast and there is not a faster code path at this time. See bug 595688 for details.

webview_android.notes: From version 3 to 4.3, there is a serious bug where text-rendering: optimizeLegibility causes custom web fonts to not render. This was fixed in version 4.4.

painting.html#TextRenderingProperty.title: text-rendering

paths.html#InterfaceSVGPathElement.summary: The SVGPathElement interface corresponds to the path element.
paths.html#InterfaceSVGPathElement.title: SVGPathElement

paths.html#PathElement.summary: The path SVG element is the generic element to define a shape. All the basic shapes can be created with a path element.
paths.html#PathElement.title: <path>

pservers.html#GradientStops.summary: The stop SVG element defines the ramp of colors to use on a gradient, which is a child element to either the linearGradient or the radialGradient element.
pservers.html#GradientStops.title: <stop>

pservers.html#InterfaceSVGGradientElemen.summary: The SVGGradient interface is a base interface used by SVGLinearGradientElement and SVGRadialGradientElement.
pservers.html#InterfaceSVGGradientElemen.title: SVGGradientElement

pservers.html#InterfaceSVGLinearGradient.summary: The SVGLinearGradientElement interface corresponds to the linearGradient element.
pservers.html#InterfaceSVGLinearGradient.title: SVGLinearGradientElement

pservers.html#InterfaceSVGPatternElement.summary: The SVGPatternElement interface corresponds to the pattern element.
pservers.html#InterfaceSVGPatternElement.title: SVGPatternElement

pservers.html#InterfaceSVGRadialGradient.summary: The SVGRadialGradientElement interface corresponds to the RadialGradient element.
pservers.html#InterfaceSVGRadialGradient.title: SVGRadialGradientElement

pservers.html#InterfaceSVGStopElement.summary: The SVGStopElement interface corresponds to the stop element.
pservers.html#InterfaceSVGStopElement.title: SVGStopElement

pservers.html#LinearGradients.summary: The linearGradient SVG element lets authors define linear gradients to fill or stroke graphical elements.
pservers.html#LinearGradients.title: <linearGradient>

pservers.html#PatternElementXAttribute.summary: The x attribute defines a x-axis coordinate in the user coordinate system.
pservers.html#PatternElementXAttribute.title: x

pservers.html#PatternElementYAttribute.summary: The y attribute defines a y-axis coordinate in the user coordinate system.
pservers.html#PatternElementYAttribute.title: y

pservers.html#Patterns.summary: The pattern element defines a graphics object which can be redrawn at repeated x and y-coordinate intervals ("tiled") to cover an area.
pservers.html#Patterns.title: <pattern>

pservers.html#RadialGradients.summary: The radialGradient SVG element lets authors define radial gradients to fill or stroke graphical elements.
pservers.html#RadialGradients.title: <radialGradient>

script.html#InterfaceSVGScriptElement.summary: The SVGScriptElement interface corresponds to the SVG script element.
script.html#InterfaceSVGScriptElement.title: SVGScriptElement

script.html#ScriptElement.summary: A SVG script element is equivalent to the script element in HTML and thus is the place for scripts (e.g., ECMAScript).
script.html#ScriptElement.title: <script>

shapes.html#CircleElement.summary: The circle SVG element is an SVG basic shape, used to create circles based on a center point and a radius.
shapes.html#CircleElement.title: <circle>

shapes.html#EllipseElement.summary: The ellipse element is an SVG basic shape, used to create ellipses based on a center coordinate, and both their x and y radius.
shapes.html#EllipseElement.title: <ellipse>

shapes.html#InterfaceSVGCircleElement.summary: The SVGCircleElement interface is an interface for the circle element. The circle element is defined by the cx and cy attributes that denote the coordinates of the centre of the circle.
shapes.html#InterfaceSVGCircleElement.title: SVGCircleElement

shapes.html#InterfaceSVGLineElement.summary: The SVGLineElement interface provides access to the properties of line elements, as well as methods to manipulate them.

shapes.html#InterfaceSVGRectElement.summary: The SVGRect represents a rectangle. Rectangles consist of an x and y coordinate pair identifying a minimum x value, a minimum y value, and a width and height, which are constrained to be non-negative.
shapes.html#InterfaceSVGRectElement.title: SVGRect

shapes.html#LineElement.summary: The line element is an SVG basic shape used to create a line connecting two points.
shapes.html#LineElement.title: <line>

shapes.html#PolygonElement.summary: The polygon element defines a closed shape consisting of a set of connected straight line segments. The last point is connected to the first point. For open shapes see the polyline element.
shapes.html#PolygonElement.title: <polygon>

shapes.html#PolylineElement.summary: The polyline SVG element is an SVG basic shape that creates straight lines connecting several points. Typically a polyline is used to create open shapes as the last point doesn't have to be connected to the first point. For closed shapes see the polygon element.
shapes.html#PolylineElement.title: <polyline>

shapes.html#RectElement.summary: The rect element is a basic SVG shape that creates rectangles, defined by their corner's position, their width, and their height. The rectangles may have their corners rounded.
shapes.html#RectElement.title: <rect>

shapes.html#RectElementXAttribute.summary: The x attribute defines a x-axis coordinate in the user coordinate system.
shapes.html#RectElementXAttribute.title: x

shapes.html#RectElementYAttribute.summary: The y attribute defines a y-axis coordinate in the user coordinate system.
shapes.html#RectElementYAttribute.title: y

struct.html#DescriptionAndTitleElements.summary: Each container element or graphics element in an SVG drawing can supply a description string using the desc element where the description is text-only.
struct.html#DescriptionAndTitleElements.title: <desc>

struct.html#DescriptionAndTitleElements.summary: Each container element or graphics element in an SVG drawing can supply a title element containing a description string where the description is text-only. When the current SVG document fragment is rendered as SVG on visual media, title element is not rendered as part of the graphics. However, some user agents may, for example, display the title element as a tooltip. Alternate presentations are possible, both visual and aural, which display the title element but do not display path elements or other graphics elements. The title element generally improves accessibility of SVG documents.
struct.html#DescriptionAndTitleElements.title: <title>

struct.html#Groups.summary: The g SVG element is a container used to group other SVG elements.
struct.html#Groups.title: <g>

struct.html#Head.summary: The defs element is used to store graphical objects that will be used at a later time. Objects created inside a defs element are not rendered directly. To display them you have to reference them (with a use element for example).
struct.html#Head.title: <defs>

struct.html#ImageElement.summary: The image SVG element includes images inside SVG documents. It can display raster image files or other SVG files.
struct.html#ImageElement.title: <image>

struct.html#InterfaceSVGUseElement.summary: The SVGUseElement interface corresponds to the use element.

struct.html#NewDocument.summary: The svg element is a container that defines a new coordinate system and viewport. It is used as the outermost element of any SVG document but it can also be used to embed a SVG fragment inside any SVG or HTML document.

struct.html#SwitchElement.summary: The switch SVG element evaluates the requiredFeatures, requiredExtensions and systemLanguage attributes on its direct child elements in order, and then processes and renders the first child for which these attributes evaluate to true. All others will be bypassed and therefore not rendered. If the child element is a container element such as a g, then the entire subtree is either processed/rendered or bypassed/not rendered.
struct.html#SwitchElement.title: <switch>

struct.html#SymbolElement.summary: The symbol element is used to define graphical template objects which can be instantiated by a use element.
struct.html#SymbolElement.title: <symbol>

struct.html#UseElement.summary: The use element takes nodes from within the SVG document, and duplicates them somewhere else.

notes: For years, Firefox has suffered from a bug whereby it doesn't completely follow the use cascading rules (see bug 265894). A fix is documented by Amelia Bellamy-Royds on StackOverflow. The good news is that this is finally fixed as of Firefox 56.

text.html#TextElementTextLengthAttribute.summary: The textLength attribute, available on SVG text and tspan elements,  lets you specify the width of the space into which the text will draw. The user agent will ensure that the text does not extend farther than that distance, using the method or methods specified by the lengthAdjust attribute. By default, only the spacing between characters is adjusted, but the glyph size can also be adjusted if you change lengthAdjust.

text.html#TextPathElement.summary: In addition to text drawn in a straight line, SVG also includes the ability to place text along the shape of a path element. To specify that a block of text is to be rendered along the shape of a path, include the given text within a textPath element which includes an href attribute with a reference to a path element.

notes: Until Safari 6, textPath was not re-rendered when the referenced path was changed dynamically (see bug 15799)

types.html#InterfaceSVGAngle.summary: The SVGAngle interface is used to represent a value that can be an angle or number value. An SVGAngle reflected through the animVal attribute is always read only.
types.html#InterfaceSVGAngle.title: SVGAngle

types.html#InterfaceSVGElement.summary: All of the SVG DOM interfaces that correspond directly to elements in the SVG language derive from the SVGElement interface.
types.html#InterfaceSVGElement.title: SVGElement

types.html#InterfaceSVGGeometryElement.summary: The SVGTextPositioningElement interface is implemented by elements that support attributes that position individual text glyphs. It is inherited by SVGTextElement, SVGTSpanElement, SVGTRefElement and SVGAltGlyphElement.
types.html#InterfaceSVGGeometryElement.title: SVGTextPositioningElement

types.html#InterfaceSVGNumber.summary: The SVGNumber interface corresponds to the number basic data type.
types.html#InterfaceSVGNumber.title: SVGNumber

types.html#InterfaceSVGTests.summary: The SVGTests interface is used to reflect conditional processing attributes and is mixed into other interfaces for elements that support these attributes.
types.html#InterfaceSVGTests.title: SVGTests

types.html#InterfaceSVGURIReference.summary: The SVGURIReference interface is used to reflect the href attribute and the deprecated xlink:href attribute.
types.html#InterfaceSVGURIReference.title: SVGURIReference

types.html#InterfaceSVGUnitTypes.summary: The SVGUnitTypes interface defines a commonly used set of constants used for reflecting gradientUnits, patternContentUnits and other similar attributes.
types.html#InterfaceSVGUnitTypes.title: SVGUnitTypes

types.html#InterfaceSVGZoomAndPan.summary: The SVGZoomAndPan interface is used to reflect the zoomAndPan attribute, and is mixed in to other interfaces for elements that support this attribute.
types.html#InterfaceSVGZoomAndPan.title: SVGZoomAndPan
